\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Case Study: DesignOps and Design Systems @ Careerstart & WAE\
Building a Scalable DesignOps System for a Staffing App\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Overview\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 As the head of product design and UX in a fast-paced startup environment, I led the creation of a scalable DesignOps ecosystem that supported not only the technical and organizational aspects of our design workflow but also the hands-on design, testing, and validation of the staffing app itself. My role encompassed a broad range of responsibilities\'97from designing and iterating the core product to managing stakeholder engagement, hiring and guiding team members, and establishing a high-functioning DesignOps framework that enabled seamless collaboration and rapid iteration. This case study illustrates how these efforts resulted in a design environment that drove efficiency, alignment, and scalability across our product development process.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 DesignOps Strategy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 To support a dynamic and adaptable design environment, I organized our DesignOps around several foundational pillars: efficient processes, centralized documentation, accessible design resources, and a robust design system. This strategy was designed to serve as the backbone of our workflow, enabling our team to transition smoothly from ideation through to execution while fostering cross-functional alignment and maintaining high standards for both user experience and product quality.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Building a System for Rapid Iteration and Stakeholder Alignment\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 In addition to my product design responsibilities, I created a structured environment that supported fast-paced iteration and kept all stakeholders informed and engaged. The goals here were to enable efficient design updates, transparent communication, and real-time feedback loops. Key steps included:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Integrated Figma and Jira Workflows: Figma served as the primary design platform, with Jira used to track project tasks alongside engineering. This integration enabled live updates and allowed team members to monitor feedback, status changes, and design evolution seamlessly.\
\uc0\u8259 	File Structuring and Status Indicators: I established a clear labeling system using emojis and figma labelling templates to help team members quickly identify a file\'92s purpose, stage, and relevance. This minimized friction across teams, especially during critical handoffs.\
\uc0\u8259 	Stakeholder Engagement through Reviews and Workshops: Regular design reviews and cross-departmental workshops encouraged feedback at key stages, helping to align our work with user needs and business objectives. This process was essential for securing stakeholder buy-in and ensuring our approach reflected strategic priorities.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 DesignOps Framework: Key Components\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 0.	Structured File Organization for Transparency and Access: Each design file followed a standardized organization system, including specific naming conventions, hierarchical page structures, and easy-to-navigate frames. This provided instant clarity for all team members on file content and version, enhancing collaboration.\
0.	Component Library with Atomic Design Principles: I created a component library in Figma structured by atomic design principles. Each component was standardized with naming conventions and specific behaviors, making them reusable and scalable as the product evolved.\
0.	Centralized Documentation Hub: A Documentation Wiki acted as a single source of truth, housing meeting notes, performance metrics, UX patterns, and live links to Figma files. This centralization allowed stakeholders and team members to access current resources independently, enabling faster decision-making and reducing dependency on individual team members.\
0.	User Testing and Prototyping for Continuous Feedback: User-centered testing was a key element of our process. We conducted remote and in-person testing with Figma prototypes, gathering a blend of quantitative and qualitative insights. This feedback loop enabled me to refine designs iteratively and tailor the product to our users\'92 needs.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Project File Structure\
A robust file structure in Figma was essential for maintaining clarity and consistency across all stages of the project. I created a system that facilitated easy access to current designs and streamlined collaboration across teams:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Status Indicators: We used emojis as visual prefixes to indicate designer\'92s figma file status: \u55357 \u56999  for in-progress work, \u55358 \u56605  for developer handoff, and \u55358 \u56810  for testing files. This quick reference allowed team members to navigate our files efficiently.\
\uc0\u8259 	Working vs. Handoff Files: I established distinct files for active design work and developer-ready handoffs. All initial component and screen design took place in working files, and only instances of validated components were moved into handoff files. This ensured that developers always referenced fully approved, up-to-date designs.\
\uc0\u8259 	Thumbnail Templates for Visual Organization: Standardized thumbnail templates helped team members identify project files at a glance, saving time and reducing confusion. These templates displayed project name, status, and version, reinforcing the consistency and accessibility of our design library.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Driving Cross-Departmental Collaboration\
Figma as a Collaborative Hub: Figma became our central design hub, breaking down silos and enabling cross-departmental collaboration in real time. This integration supported each phase of the project lifecycle, providing an accessible platform for design, feedback, and iteration.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Real-Time Design Reviews: In Figma, design reviews became a platform for cross-departmental feedback, allowing team members to annotate directly on files and streamline the decision-making process.\
\uc0\u8259 	Documentation Integration with Jira: Each Figma design task linked to a corresponding Jira ticket, creating a seamless transition between design and engineering teams\'92 development phases. This ensured that all relevant documentation and feedback were accessible, allowing for traceable task management across teams.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Jira for Structured Task Management: Implementing Jira in our workflow allowed us to track each task clearly and align it with sprint schedules.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Design Task Tracking and Prioritization: Every design task was managed through Jira, enabling us to maintain a centralized backlog and set priorities within each sprint.\
\uc0\u8259 	Swimlane Organization for Workflow Clarity: We used swimlanes like \'93Design Review\'94 and \'93Technical Review\'94 to manage workflows, which supported efficient handoffs and minimized the risk of rework.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Developing a Scalable Component Library\
Our component library in Figma was designed for both flexibility and scalability, enabling consistency across the app\'92s UI and enhancing efficiency during the design phase.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Atomic Design Hierarchy: Components were organized by atomic design principles into atoms, molecules, and organisms, forming a reusable framework. This structure allowed our team to maintain a consistent design language across app features.\
\uc0\u8259 	Precise Naming Conventions: Each component followed a standardized naming convention according to best practices (e.g., Button/Primary/Large/Default), which simplified retrieval and ensured accurate application.\
\uc0\u8259 	Variants and Nested Components: By creating variants and nesting components, we allowed for flexible, scalable design options while reducing redundant work across screens and workflows.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 User Testing and Continuous Prototyping\
I prioritized a user-centered approach, integrating user feedback at every stage of the design process to align our product with real-world needs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Interactive Prototypes: Figma prototypes allowed us to illustrate and test full user flows and interface interactions in real-time, gathering valuable insights to inform design decisions.\
\uc0\u8259 	Data-Driven Iteration: Insights from testing helped us make data-driven adjustments to the product, prioritizing changes that directly impacted the user experience.\
\uc0\u8259 	Stakeholder Transparency: Prototypes were shared with stakeholders to illustrate functionality, updated designs, and keep them informed of user testing outcomes, which facilitated more informed decision-making and alignment on design directions.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Comprehensive Documentation and Handoff\
Ensuring a seamless, accurate transition from design to development was central to our DesignOps strategy. Our documentation and handoff process created a centralized, consistent experience for all stakeholders, with precise versioning and annotation details that allowed team members to trace any component to its exact iteration.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Centralized Handoff Files: Published handoff files in Figma provided developers with up-to-date, approved designs, annotated with interaction notes, component details, and usage instructions. These files were meticulously organized to reduce ambiguity and ensure developers accessed only final, validated designs.\
\uc0\u8259 	Realtime Automatic Documentation Updates: Our system supported controlled cascading of version updates from designers\'92 working files to final handoff files. Approved changes to any component flowed automatically through all linked instances, including those in other areas of documentation, maintaining consistency across all design assets and documentation. This structure ensured that stakeholders and developers always accessed the most current and accurate versions.\
\uc0\u8259 	Granular Versioning and Naming Conventions: To keep track of each design iteration, version numbers and naming conventions were implemented at both the file and individual component levels:\
\uc0\u8259 	File-Level Versioning: Each file included a version indicator in its name, clearly specifying the current iteration stage (e.g., v1.2, v2.1).\
\uc0\u8259 	Component and Frame Naming and Versioning: Each screen and component within the file carried its own version indicator and naming convention, allowing team members to identify the exact version of any design element. This included sequential versioning (e.g., 1.01.01 for versioned screens) and variant tags for components, which ensured that all team members could quickly verify they were working with the latest approved design iteration.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Together, these practices created a transparent, up-to-date documentation and handoff process that minimized misunderstandings, maintained alignment, and provided a reliable reference point for every stage of design and development.\
Results\
Implementing this DesignOps framework yielded measurable benefits:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8259 	Increased Efficiency: The centralized system reduced time spent on file organization and minimized dependency on individual team members, allowing the team to focus on quality and rapid iteration.\
\uc0\u8259 	Enhanced Consistency: A structured component library and streamlined workflows ensured uniformity and accuracy across app features, simplifying collaboration between designers and developers.\
\uc0\u8259 	Strengthened Cross-Functional Collaboration: Figma and Jira integration provided real-time access and transparency, minimizing rework and facilitating agile, user-centered development.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Conclusion\
My role in building and managing this DesignOps environment allowed our team to operate with agility and alignment across design, development, and product teams, creating a foundation that will continue to support our evolving needs. This comprehensive system enabled rapid iterations, stakeholder alignment, and data-driven decisions, strengthening our design impact and setting a strong foundation for the future scalability of both the team and the product.\
This version reflects your leadership in creating both the product and a robust design operations framework, while emphasizing the impact on team collaboration, user-focused design, and process scalability. Let me know if you\'92d like further adjustments to any sections.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

